{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's ghazal, the **matla** (opening couplet) is:\n\n> Yoon to ae bazm-e-jahan! dilkash thay hungamay teray  \n> Ik zara afsurdagi teray tamashaon mein thi[^1]\n\nIts claim, in English translation, is concessive: the spectacles (*hungamay*) of the worldly stage (*bazm-e-jahan*) were indeed enchanting (*dilkash*), yet they were tinged with melancholy (*afsurdagi*) among the onlookers (*tamashai*).[^2]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, chapter 4 (\"Yoon to ae bazm-e-jahan! dilkash thay hungamay teray\"), transliteration, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/04-yoon-to-ae-bazm-e-jahan-dilkash-thay-hungamay-tera/transliteration/#p-988c94).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, chapter 4 (\"Yoon to ae bazm-e-jahan! dilkash thay hungamay teray\"), translation, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/04-yoon-to-ae-bazm-e-jahan-dilkash-thay-hungamay-tera/translation/#p-6fed75).",
